    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Columbia S. C.</placeName>, <date>Sept 21,
                '52</date></p>
            <p>
                <sic>
                    <addressee>Rev. Lesser Esq.</addressee>
                </sic>
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I herewith take the liberty to turn to<lb/> you with the request to
                send me the<lb/> Occident of which you are the editor. At<lb/> the same time I want
                to tell you of the<lb/> condition in which our Community finds<lb/> itself. We have
                a Hazan here. But, as<lb/> you know, we have no Shohet. Never-<lb/>theless I have
                occasionally found<lb/> a seal "Kosher" on the meat. With<lb/> regard to this I have
                naturally spoken<lb/> frequently. The "Yehudin" here are,<lb/> however, such
                ignoramuses that they<lb/> are perfectly content if they see a seal<lb/> on the
                meat, and do not bother to know<lb/> who <del>put</del> attached it, whether a
                man<lb/> who knows anything about slaughtering<lb/> or not, whether he has legal permission<lb/>
                <add>Kaballa</add> to slaughter, or not. To them<lb/> these things do not matter.
                But it is</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>2</p>
            <p>wrong of a man who has no <hi rend="underline">Kaballa</hi><lb/> and knows nothing of
                Shehita, to act as<lb/> Shohet for a community. It is even worse<lb/> for a man who
                wants to live as a Jew<lb/> and is in this way deprived of the op-<lb/>portunity.
                For when we want to obtain<lb/> a pious Jew as Shohet, he can find<lb/> no welcome
                here, since people say<lb/> "we obtain our meat properly slaughtered<lb/> and have
                no need for a shohet."</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">You must, therefore, agree with me<lb/> that a man such as this
                cannot be<lb/> called a Jew. For whatever he may do<lb/> for himself, to slaughter
                for a community<lb/> and to hang a seal on the meat so that<lb/> it might be sold as
                kosher, is not<lb/> the work of an upright Jew. Such action<lb/> is hypocrisy and
                pious swindle,<lb/> as you must agree.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">That is why I turned to you, and<lb/> am sending you one of the
                seals which<lb/> I <del>be</del> removed from the meat only this</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>3</p>
            <p>morning when I was in the market.<lb/> I hope some good will come of your<lb/> making
                this matter public.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I shall be in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> in a<lb/> few
                weeks, and shall at the same time<lb/> purchase several holiday prayer books from
                you<lb/> of which I have need.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In the hope that this letter will<lb/> find you in good health,
                and<lb/> that you will send me the Occident,<lb/> I remain<lb/> Your devoted
                friend,</p>
            <p>
                <persName role="author">L. Elias</persName>
            </p>
            <p>Please send the Occident begin<lb/>ning with <date>Rosh ha-Shana</date></p>
        </body>
